I study social work to help children who are harmed or not cared for; and to support troubled families. I offer three important things: service to others, respect for everyone, and being good. I will keep learning to stay good at my work.

I always wanted to help others, but I did not know what job to do. In high school and college, I saw many people not deal with their problems and use bad ways to handle them. I chose to study Psychology at Piedmont College. Even after graduation, I was not sure about a job.

One day, I helped a boy who was harmed by his parents. I talked to the police and his parents. This made me think about becoming a social worker.

Social justice is important in social work. Society says each person is important, but we often want to be like others. I do not want to do this. I fought against injustice in high school and college. I am different from others and I believe in fairness. I will continue to fight for this.

The paper discusses biological and sociocultural models related to insomnia. The biological model focuses on inherited genes and health problems. The sociocultural model looks at environment, race, ethnicity, and social status.

The paper reviews insomnia and explains how it affects sleep. It discusses primary sleep disorders like insomnia and hypersomnia. Primary insomnia is when it is hard to fall asleep or stay asleep. Hypersomnia is when it is hard to stay awake. People with insomnia may have other sleep problems, like Narcolepsy, breathing problems, or rhythm problems.

The biological model looks at genes and health issues. It explains how neurons in the brain help control sleep. A study with mice showed that receptors called GABAB can help control sleep. If these receptors are not working correctly, people may have sleep problems. This suggests that sleep problems can be passed down in families. If this receptor is not working, it can cause sleep problems.

The sociocultural model looks at how environment and culture can affect sleep. If a person inherits a sleep problem from their family, it can affect their daily life. They may have trouble focusing at school or work. They may also have problems with daily tasks and activities.

This paper covers three parts: definition, diagnosis, and helping a student with CAPD in a classroom.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) or Auditory Processing Disorder (APD) is when the brain does not process sound properly. People with CAPD can hear normally, but the brain does not understand or organize what is heard correctly.

CAPD was first called "auditory imperception" in the 1950s. Tests for it were created by Italian researchers in the 1950s and 1960s. A national conference in 1977 helped researchers learn more about CAPD.

People with CAPD may struggle to:
- hear sound in space
- tell different sounds apart
- recognize sound patterns
- understand changes in speech
- hear sounds after other sounds
- understand and act on sound clues
- remember the order of sounds

To diagnose CAPD, a person must be tested by a professional. Tests include questionnaires, listening, and measuring responses to sounds. No single test is used, and there is no known cause.

Professionals use different tests to evaluate hearing and sound understanding. These tests ask people to distinguish between sounds, like words or numbers, or measure responses to sounds in the ear.

Twelfth Night shows that hiding in disguise is useful for a while, but in the end, a person must stop the deception or lose their true self. Ending deception can cause problems. Some may be hurt if they find out they were tricked. The issue of changing gender roles is complex. Why does a person need to hide their real identity? In Viola's case, she needs to become a man to protect herself in a new country. This works, but she has no female friends. Olivia loves Cesario, who is really Viola. Viola also has feelings for Orsino. These feelings may help Olivia and Orsino deal with their hidden feelings. For example, Olivia might like women, but she likes Cesario because he looks like a man. She then likes Sebastian, who is Viola's brother. So, Olivia's feelings change quickly.

German colonial rule was very harsh, especially for the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. But not all of German's colonial empire was the same. Education was also different in each colony.

In German East Africa, like Tanganyika, the government taught many Africans. In Kamerun and other colonies, education was also good. But in South West Africa, which is now Namibia, it was different. The government did not teach the native people much. Missionaries taught them, but they had little support from the government.

The government did teach European people. They made schools for Europeans and helped missionaries more. These schools had long effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. Most Africans in South West Africa did not learn to read or write.

Many reasons caused these differences. This paper wants to study these reasons, especially new research about what settlers and colonial leaders thought about Africans.

There is much writing about education in German's colonial empire. Most of the writing is in German, from the early 20th century. Some later English books compare education in different colonies. Cohen's book about education in South West Africa and East Africa is the most important for this paper. Cohen says the big settler population in South West Africa made its education system different.

South West Africa had a moderate climate, but much of the land is desert. Many Europeans lived there because of the good conditions. By 1913, there were nearly 15,000 whites in South West Africa. In East Africa, the next biggest colony, there were only 5,336 Europeans.

Popular music has many sounds. It is hard to list all the kinds. Many genres like rap, rock, country, jazz, and folk have smaller kinds. Heavy metal is a big kind of rock. It is different 40 years ago. It has many emotions. It has dark feelings. People make new kinds of heavy metal. Today, there are many kinds of heavy metal. It is hard to know what it is. Heavy metal is a music movement. It is strong music. It has dark feelings. It is like a drug. It has dark, strange feelings. It is like the Romantic Era. This is a song by the Beatles. It shows dark feelings. It is like the Rolling Stones. Heavy metal is a strong music.

Henri Rousseau wanted to be famous and loved by other artists. Before him, Surrealists painted dreams. But Rousseau painted his own dreams too. His painting The Dream shows a woman who sees beautiful things in her dream. This painting shows Rousseau's hopes and struggles. He wanted to be accepted by the art world. He felt he could either copy other styles or be different. Rousseau had a hard life. He started painting late and had no training. His first wife died, and he lost eight children. He wanted to escape his sadness by painting. He was a folk painter and wished to be like other artists. Many artists were famous at the same time as Rousseau. He wanted to be famous too. But he did not succeed until later. He did not get recognition until around the same time as Matisse. They were different. Matisse was afraid of painting in a boring way. Rousseau wanted to paint a very common way so people would like his work. He wanted to be part of the Artiste Français.

Many wise people think there is a close connection between ethics (morals) and beauty. I think this is true. John Keats says, "Beauty is truth, truth beauty— That is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Most of what we learn in life comes from education or experience. But we also understand ethics and beauty without learning them in these ways. Ethics and aesthetics (beauty) try to explain, not tell us what to do. We study morality and beauty to understand why something is good or beautiful, not to judge or create good art or behavior.

More to the point, when we discuss art or morals, we can't fully describe why something is good or beautiful. For example, talking about the Mona Lisa may mention things like foreground, background, contrast, or culture. But in the end, we can't explain why it's good art. When asked about favorite art or literature, we often hear, "There's just something about it," before a more complex explanation. I believe that art and morals can't be fully described. Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." No matter how well we describe a book, there is something more. Ethics is also like this. Wittgenstein says, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendental." I think this "something" is the most powerful part of art and morality. It connects ethics and aesthetics because they both affect us in a similar way.

I believe art and morality are close because we experience them deeply, but can't fully explain them. This is even more true for literature. McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from other arts is its moral quality. Moral standards are important to literature, as they are to life itself. Literature is important because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is strong and united. It has a unique culture from Munich in the Alps to Kiel by the Baltic Sea. The culture can also be seen in Cologne on the Rhine River, through the center of Germany to Dresden on the Elbe River. Germany was formed by different tribes and peoples. The name "Germany" comes from the ancient Germans. The name may come from a Germanic tribe called the Tungrians, or it may be from a spear or a loud shout. Roman historians wrote about the Germans. They said that Germans were not mixed with other races. They came to Germany from other places. The Romans traded with the Germans and used them in their army.

I looked at the toilet. I did not understand how to clean it. A book I read told me how to draw. I used a frame to see the bowl of fruit. But I could not use it for the toilet. I was confused. I tried to clean the toilet with a mop. It was hard. I tried to flush the toilet. But the brown package did not move. I had to use toilet paper. I wrapped it around my hand. I put my hand into the toilet. I cleaned it. I felt bad about the toilet. But I did this work at a job. I did this job for money.

Teenagers die in car accidents. Many things cause this problem. The National Institutes of Health says teen brains are not ready for driving. Teens also lack driving experience. This causes more accidents, rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens also have more accidents when they drive with friends. A study showed this. California and other states try to make teen driving safer. They limit driving hours and passengers. But these rules are not enough. Teenagers are not ready to drive safely. Marvin Zuckerman, a psychologist, says 18 is too young for a full driver's license. USA Today reports that teens under 19-20 like to take risks. So, delaying driving until this desire goes away makes sense. If we give driver's licenses to young teens, more accidents will happen. The death toll will be high in the next few years. Baby Boomers' children will be able to drive by 2010. Legislation could be simple. Schools could teach driving, but no one under 18 could drive a car. A permit could be given before a full license. A certain number of practice hours would be required. The number could be based on other states' requirements. Uniform, national rules would protect teens across the country. This is not a new idea.

I looked at many early Edison films at the Library of Congress. There were 15 trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use tricks to create illusions. I studied how to describe the tricks in most of these films. I also looked at how some of the later films differ. In many trick films, the camera does not move. The films are set in a frontal proscenium and use long or medium shots, not close-ups. For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors move side-to-side but the camera does not move. Most early trick films have one shot that is one film. They are short, usually about a minute, and show simple tricks like magic. However, a trick film's one shot can be made with many small shots joined together. Look at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895) for a good example.

John Taylor of Caroline was a early and strong supporter of Republicanism. He was mainly a farmer, but his short political career made him known for his strong beliefs in personal freedom and government. His love for farming was the center of his thoughts about government. He wanted to keep and improve this important job.

Taylor thought the United States could make a perfect system because there was no old tradition to stop it. He believed people have natural rights that are connected, meaning if one is taken away, they all suffer. These rights should be beyond government control. He said evil people with strength and bad thoughts only get ahead in a wild world, but in a civilization, this should not happen.

To create a good society, Taylor said a government must understand that humans are good and bad. He believed a government should protect private property, improve farming, and stop capitalism. He thought a government with good principles would be fair, no matter who runs it. He said self-interest is part of humans, but it becomes bad when it hurts others. A good government must watch carefully to keep people's bad side in control.

Taylor and other strong Republicans of his time wanted a strict interpretation of the Constitution. They wanted a small Federal government with only the powers clearly stated. They knew a big government could be bad. But they also said a simple, direct reading of the Constitution could become corrupt. They thought the Declaration of Independence was the true law of the United States because it said the country is a group of independent states, not just one nation.

We look at Figure 17. There was a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month. This was not good. We do not know why this happened. Maybe it was because it was winter in New England, so fewer people commuted by bicycle or on foot. Also, December is the end of the school year. People are busy with schoolwork and grades. They might have forgotten about the commuter log. December also has many holidays. School is out for a month. When classes start again in January, there are fewer commuter logs. We think the project started with a lot of energy, but it died down. To fix this, we made a special week called Carpool Challenge Week in March. This helped increase log submissions. We also had a problem with people liking to drive their cars, so we gave out many prizes. These prizes included gift certificates to local stores and a massage therapist. We also thought bigger prizes like a bicycle or car could help. The prizes did not change during the project. If we had said we would give away a bicycle in December and a car in January, maybe more people would have joined.

An ETF, or exchange traded fund, is a security that follows an index, a commodity, or a group of assets, like an index fund. It trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF gives you the benefits of an index fund and single stock ownership, like the ability to sell short or buy on margin. You can buy as few as one share at a time. ETFs usually have lower fees than mutual funds, but you pay a commission on each trade, like you do with stocks.

There are many kinds of ETFs to choose from. But it's good to check if the stated benefits, like diversification, really exist. We will look at the ETF IHF and compare it with the top 10 holdings to see if owning one ETF is as good as owning the stocks directly. We will also see if there are better ways to group the same stocks to get a better return.

We will only look at the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. Here are the top 10 holdings and their percentages:

| Stock | Percentage of Total Assets |
| --- | --- |
| Stock 1 | 10.00% |
| Stock 2 | 15.00% |
| Stock 3 | 10.00% |
| Stock 4 | 8.00% |
| Stock 5 | 5.00% |
| Stock 6 | 8.00% |
| Stock 7 | 5.00% |
| Stock 8 | 5.00% |
| Stock 9 | 2.00% |
| Stock 10 | 3.58% |

To compare the ETF and the top 10 holdings, we can calculate the Beta and return of a portfolio made up of these 10 stocks in the same proportions as the ETF. The chart below shows the results:

| Portfolio | Beta | Return |
| --- | --- | --- |
| ETF IHF | 0.85 | 10.00% |
| Top 10 Holdings | 0.73 | 16.11% |

The portfolio with just the top 10 holdings has a higher return (16.11%) and a lower Beta (0.73) than the ETF IHF. But we need to see if these differences are statistically significant.

To do this, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compare it to the ETF IHF.

Edgar Allan Poe wrote a poem called "Dream-Land". He used the name "Thulé" in this poem. This name came from the Greek word for the edge of the known world. Poe liked to read German books. He was interested in a writer named Goethe. Goethe's poem "The King of Thulé" is about a king who is sad because his wife died. Poe's poem "Dream-Land" is similar to this. In both poems, the speaker is sad and lonely. Poe used "Thulé" twice in his other writings. Poe liked Goethe's work. He admired another writer named Tennyson, who also liked Goethe. So, Poe knew about Goethe's poems.

Under California law, could a customer injured after slipping on applesauce in a store get punitive damages? The store manager knew about the spill and did not clean it for thirty minutes because he was eating.

A judge is unlikely to dismiss the claim. To get punitive damages, the customer must show the store manager acted with willful disregard for the probable harm and that his actions were despicable. The manager knew about past injuries but did not clean the spill.

On October 13, 2009, an employee told the manager about the applesauce spill. The manager said he was eating dinner and did not have time to clean it. Another employee also told the manager about the spill, but he did not clean it. At 5:30 pm, Jennifer Palmer slipped and fell, getting a serious back injury.

This happened in a store that had six slip-and-fall accidents in 2009. The manager did not do anything to make the store safer. So, Palmer is suing for compensatory and punitive damages. We are considering a motion to stop the punitive damage claim.

In California, a plaintiff can get punitive damages for conduct with “oppression, fraud, or malice.” If the conduct was not deliberate, it must be “despicable” and done with a willful disregard for the safety of others. Courts say conduct is malicious if the defendant knew the harm would happen and did not try to avoid it.

In 2015, I studied Islam at CBC.  We discussed whether Islam is a hostile religion.  This is still important today.  After 9/11, the media showed different views of Islam.  In 2001, we could not have had a Muslim president like Barack Obama.
The story of Muhammad is interesting.  It says he was kind and wise.  But some people think he forced people to become Muslim.  He conquered tribes and made them follow Islam.  The story also has some similarities with Jesus.  For example, Muhammad multiplied food to feed many people.  But this makes Jesus' miracles less special.
The stories in the biography are not always true.  People tell stories about stories.  This makes it hard to know what is real.  The biography makes Muhammad look good and humble.  But history shows he was not always gentle.  Many Muslims might not know this.

Jesus' teachings and beliefs were quickly changed after his life. Today, many people know about this change, and they want to learn more about what Jesus really said. In the future, many Christians will try to understand Jesus' ideas better. They will remove many added teachings, like if they are removing layers of an onion. They will try to follow only Jesus' ideas. When this happens in the United States and Europe, the church will be strong. However, there will be less diversity in beliefs and practices. In history, there have been many reversals. For example, Christians were once persecuted, but later the Roman Empire became Christian. In the future, there will be a big change in the Christian religion. It will be like going back in time to the period of Jesus, and people will follow only his teachings. This change will happen because people will understand Jesus' words as metaphors, not as literal statements.

I believe that The Jungle shows how people are naturally selfish. They only care about themselves and their own good, not about others who may be worse off. The book shows this in many ways. The owners and managers of big factories only want to make their companies big and powerful. They do not care about people or animals that get hurt. The smoke from factories and waste from animal pens show this. Workers also face bad conditions and long hours. There are few laws to protect them. Workers might get fired without warning or help finding jobs. This makes workers feel like slaves, "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, hanging always on the verge of starvation and dependent for its opportunities of life upon the whim of men every bit as brutal and unscrupulous as the old-time slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is exactly as inevitable, and as prevalent, as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Many writers use different methods to make readers feel or think a certain way about important topics. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these methods in his book The Great Gatsby. He often uses words that do not usually go together to make readers feel a certain way. He also uses symbols to show meanings. In The Great Gatsby, Fitzgerald makes colors like gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink have special meanings.

Fitzgerald uses white/gray to show uniformity. He says white is nicer and better than gray. At the beginning of the book, everyone wears white: Daisy, Jordan, Nick, Tom, and people at Gatsby's party. Also, many ordinary things are white or gray: Nick goes down "white chasms," people have "gray names," and places are "gray land." After making these meanings, Fitzgerald uses white/gray to show things that are unimportant or uniform.

This starts with Daisy. After a long time without white/gray, Fitzgerald describes Daisy in a white dress. Readers see Daisy as less important, just something Gatsby wants. Fitzgerald does this more around Daisy, with her fur collar being "gray" and her dress being "white."

San Diego County has good weather for growing plants. Many people like to eat tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. The area has many farms that sell organic food to the community. People like organic eggs and milk. Some farms offer tours and places to watch birds. This land could help with government programs and protect the environment. Organic farming has more work and may have lower yields. It also helps many animals live near the farm. The land near Potrero has many types of plants and animals. Some are in danger, like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and the mountain yellow-legged frog. Native Americans lived there long ago. Cattle ranchers used the land in the 1800s. The land can be used for tourism and learning.

Culture is important in negotiation. Culture is what a group of people believe and do. It is not the same for everyone. Statements like "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are accommodating" are not always true. Understanding a culture's general beliefs is useful, but it is better to understand how a culture's beliefs affect a negotiation. When meeting a foreign culture, people often compare it to their own culture. To understand a foreign culture, study its history and understand its feelings. Do not judge or change a culture. Accept it as it is and work within its rules. If a negotiator is weak, this is especially important. If in a foreign place, respecting local traditions helps move the negotiation forward. Culture is not only about countries. Many companies have their own culture. This can affect how employees work, dress, and communicate. Some companies encourage helping the community, while others do not. Understanding these differences helps in negotiations.

Values are also important. They explain why a culture believes what it does. If a culture values saving face, it will not publicly shame others to win a negotiation. If a culture values a good bargain, it will not settle quickly. Knowing these things helps before starting a negotiation. But a negotiator should also learn about their opponent to make the negotiation better.

“The fool thinks there is no God.” This idea is found in Psalm 14 of the Christian Bible and is used in St. Anselm’s argument about God. Thomas Aquinas also believes this. We will compare their arguments because they both believe in the same God, the one in the Bible. To do this, we assume that both are right in their belief of God.

St. Anselm says God is in our minds. He thinks we can find God’s proof by looking inside ourselves, not needing any outside evidence. This is called faith. It is different from Thomas Aquinas’s idea.

Thomas Aquinas says God can be proven with reason and evidence. He uses five arguments: change, cause, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. He shows that God is necessary and logical. If you know a puzzle is missing a piece, you can know the piece exists without seeing it.

Sometime between five hundred and six hundred years ago, a prince became enlightenment and was called Buddha. He taught Buddhism. The most common type is called Theravada Buddhism. This religion is around two thousand five hundred years old. It is different now than when Buddha was alive. In the Theravada country of Sri Lanka, there is an annual water-cutting ceremony. Monks and people take part. This has special meaning even though Buddha did not teach about this event. These changes happen from inside and outside the Buddhist community. Here are some important words used in this talk. Internal means coming from Buddhists. External means from non-Buddhists. Hostile means harmful. Benign means not harmful. These words will be used often.

First, we must learn about the basic beliefs of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists follow three main things: the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is made up of three parts: Sutta Pitaka, Vinaya Pitaka, and Abhidhamma Pitaka. Sutta Pitaka is all the Suttas. Vinaya Pitaka has rules for life. Abhidhamma Pitaka has about Buddhism. We must understand Anatta, Dukkha, and Anicca to end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth. When one becomes enlightened, lobha, dosa, and moha end. In Vinaya Pitaka, life rules are for everyone. For laymen, there are five rules. For monks, there are many more rules. The most important belief is the four noble truths. First, life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be overcome.

Two countries, the United States and Mexico, had a long rivalry. This lasted from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145). The biggest fight was the Mexican-American War. This war happened from 1846 to 1848. The United States won and took Texas and the American Southwest as new land. There were many other fights between the two countries. These fights stopped just before World War I.

Like many countries, the United States and Mexico had fights because they shared a border. This often led to fights over land and resources. David M. Pletcher (1977) says that only Mexico and Cuba had long-lasting problems with the United States (p. 41). Other Latin American countries had good relations with the United States.

Religious issues also caused problems. Sally Frahm (2001) says that Americans were against Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries (p.86). This was like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. But in this case, it was about religion, not politics. The United States and Mexico both had trust issues from their history with the English and Spanish.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) write about 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most of these fights were about borders. Bandits and outlaws often attacked American border towns. Schmitt (1974) says that the fights stopped when Mexico became dependent on the United States. Finally, American interests changed from wanting more land to wanting to help Mexico economically in the late 19th century.

I became disabled suddenly and unexpectedly by an illness I did not know about. I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted safety and security. "You can always find work," people told me when I was young. So, even though I wanted to be a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing.

Now, I am 46 years old and single. I cannot work, and I have no money in the bank. I live on Social Security Disability, but every day is a struggle. Family and friends helped me all these years. I feel weak when disaster happens, but I know I could not have survived without their help.

There are always emergencies in life, big and small. No one can overcome them alone, no matter how well they prepare. Americans should learn to trust and help each other again, not just rely on big government. Our forefathers survived not by going alone, but with compassion, respect, and shared resources.

I agree that we should be prepared. I have a disaster kit with first aid, water purifying tablets, and canned food. If you have land and resources, start a small farm and can or preserve food. A wood stove is a good idea if you live in a house, not an apartment.

But while you prepare, get to know your neighbors. They can help in emergencies.

Why do organisms change over time? Are there limits on how this happens? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that even now, the zoologist has not started to describe organic forms in math language. But now, math modeling is used in some areas like mollusk skeletogenesis. Our study looks at how math models and experiments can explain how and why organisms change. We used X-ray images of Prunum to find numbers that can be used in a program called CerioShell. We made models of different shell shapes to see what changes are possible. These models are used with other studies to understand big changes in Prunum over time.

A shell is like a tube that grows around a central line. This line is called the columella. The shell grows in turns or spirals, called whorls. Each whorl has a line called a suture. The biggest whorl is the last one. The part without the last whorl is called the spire. The shell's opening is called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different directions. The usual way is with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing up. This is called an apertural view.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top and find where the first suture starts. Then draw a line through the shell. Count the whorls from this line, rounding to a quarter of a whorl. Shells can be seen as a series of openings that change over time. This path can be shown in math. Once a math formula is made, the mollusk's skeletogenesis can be changed by changing parameters.

Indonesia's neonatal and infant death rate has not changed much for ten years. The country has done well with water and sanitation goals, but child and maternal health goals are not met. This is because of many reasons. So, the health system should be strengthened instead of only focused on specific programs.

Indonesia has more births with skilled workers now, 72%. But, traditional workers like midwives cannot provide medical care if there are problems. The quality of care is not good, and there are not enough health workers in rural areas. The rich use more health services than the poor. This is because they have more money.

To improve neonatal and maternal care, Indonesia should decide whether to focus on specific programs or strengthen the health system. Specific programs are easier to plan and see results quickly. But, they can also cause problems. If too much money goes to one program, other programs suffer and workers go where the money is. Having many programs for one area can cause problems too. They can cause too much paperwork and not work together.

Victorian novels usually focus on small details and the upper class. Two books, "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights," are different. They have strange ideas and mysteries, which make the characters stronger. They show the characters' thoughts and feelings.

In "Oliver Twist," there are dreams that show Oliver's mind. He sees and hears things that are not real. This can show that Oliver does not have control over what happens to him. He feels pain, but he does not know why. He also feels defeated because he cannot stop bad things from happening.

In "Wuthering Heights," there are also dreams and strange happenings that show the characters' feelings. These dreams can show what the characters want or fear.

Two years ago, I worked at an after-school program tutoring elementary students. I helped them in any subject they needed help with. My best subjects were English and reading. One boy named Adrian needed help with reading. He spoke perfect English, but had strange reading problems. Some letters he knew, others he didn't. His mother spoke only Spanish. We struggled until I understood: Adrian knew the English alphabet. He just didn't know how to read letters. We worked on English reading, especially the alphabet. For children who speak little English, the solution is harder. It needs a combination of: dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes. I think combining these will help all children. Dual language can help all children, not just Spanish speakers. It helps them learn two languages better. Teachers don't need to be bilingual. But special bilingual helpers can help.

From when we are young, many people tell us there is something big. Some go to church or temple. Some look inside for answers. Many follow what parents teach. But some do not believe there is more than what we know. They change their minds later. Whatever we choose, we find our own way to understand it. We look for light in darkness. We search for answers to be happy.

"Cardinal," my father said. He liked this bird. We sat on the porch. Rain hit the tin roof. My father looked out, thinking. He was thin, hair less. He stared, avoiding my eyes. I felt alone, afraid. I hugged him. We sat, watching rain.

My father died in December, five days after my birthday. Medicine did not help. He lived longer, but suffered. I did not watch him die. I wanted to remember him alive. I stayed in bed, waiting for news.

No one called.

The "Gothic Novel" is an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt says in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. People have both praised and criticized Gothic novels. They are seen as having no real depth, but also as having a 'terrible sublime' quality.

The first Gothic novel was The Castle of Otranto by Horace Walpole. It combined old ideas from romances with new ones from the modern world. Walpole used old theatrical elements and new ways to show nature in a story. The Gothic genre used many ideas from medieval Gothic theatre and architecture.

Even when The Castle of Otranto was published, the word "gothic" was used for many different things. It was seen as old-fashioned and not as good as modern things. The mix of old and new made Gothic novels interesting for a long time.

One big idea in Gothic novels is chivalry. Chivalry was a way to train knights in the past. It included being brave, honorable, and skilled. Writers liked chivalry because it showed what they thought people should be like. They thought this idea was lost in the present society.

Walpole saw this in his time. He was worried about the future. He thought that the good qualities from the past were lost in his time. He showed this in his writing, especially in the character Frederic. The reader can see that Frederic has many chivalric traits. He is a prince and has suffered much. He is also supposed to be dead. His story shows the old idea of the gallant and courteous knight, but it is exaggerated.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from the point of customer order through to production, supply, and distribution. The term was first used in 1982 by Keith Oliver. It involves planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to quickly and efficiently meet customer needs. There are six key parts to a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. These are used to give the best customer service.

Production is the first step. It is the base for the whole process. Managers need to decide what, when, where, and how to produce. They look at the market to know what customers want. After understanding customer demand, managers decide what and how many products to make. They then choose the best plant for volume and quality, keeping customer needs in mind. Next, they plan workloads and maintain equipment. Production is very important. Every detail is vital.

The second key part is supply. This is about deciding which core capabilities and outsourcing partnerships are needed. A company may have different divisions for one product. Each division has different equipment and workers. The manager decides which division is best for each process. The core reason to outsource is to be fast and reduce costs, all while keeping quality high.

In Burma, a sign says Hitler is alive. Ellen Page, the actress from Juno, holds a sign with this message. Burma, also called Myanmar, has a bad government. The people have no freedom. In 2007, monks led protests. Many people died. A journalist was killed. This is not new. Many bad governments do this. They want to stop people from saying what they think. Hitler killed many Jews.

Duke Ellington wrote many songs that were long and complex. He played the piano well and led a band that played many types of music. Ellington's music showed the skills of his band members. He wrote songs that let band members play solos freely. He also wrote songs that were very organized. Ellington's music was very creative. He used different sounds and styles to make his music stand out. In his song "Creole Love Call," Ellington used a voice as an instrument. This was a new idea in jazz. The song had six parts that showed different sounds and styles. In "Hot and Bothered," Ellington used a trumpet and scat singing to make a new sound. In "It Don't Mean a Thing," he used a trombone to introduce the melody. Ellington's music was always creative and interesting.

She wanted something. She felt this desire since she was 14, and it stayed with her at 17. She wanted a person, not a thing. No boy interested her, but she was nice to everyone. Her parents were calm, but she was different. Today was not calm. Her mother was hurt. Her daughter heard her scream in the kitchen. She ran to help. Her mother said, "Take me to the hospital." She carried her to the car and drove to the hospital. Doctors took her mother to be checked. Her daughter waited and worried. Her mother fell off a step stool.

A study showed that women who follow a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet) have less chance of getting heart disease and stroke. This diet includes many plant foods, like fruits, nuts, and whole grains, and more fish. It has less animal and saturated fats. The study looked at 74,886 nurses for 20 years. It found that women who follow this diet better have a lower risk of heart disease and stroke. The study also showed that women who follow this diet better have less chance of dying from these diseases.

In 2007, the United States had a big money problem. Many jobs were lost, and big companies were in trouble. This recession is still happening now. So, why did this happen, and how can we stop it? The crisis was caused by greedy people in politics who made banks give bad loans. These bad loans were mixed together and sold, like in a game of musical chairs. When people couldn't pay their loans, the banks had no money for the rest. This made the whole economy bad.

The problem started in 1999 during the Clinton time. The president wanted to stay in power, so he made it easier to get loans. This led to many people getting loans they couldn't pay back. A reporter from the New York Times wrote about this in 1999. He said it could cause a big problem like before, when many banks went broke.

Many things happened that made the economy go down. Some people got loans that changed over time. Some loans were mixed together and sold. This made many parts of the economy depend on the housing market. When the housing market went down, the other parts of the economy also went down.

The top five U.S. investment banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007. This was a big part of the U.S. economy. Some banks were bought cheaply or went out of business. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were also in big trouble with $5 trillion in mortgage debts. They were taken over by the government in 2008.

Exposition is not easy.  It is the part of your story where you tell, not show.  This can be bad.  It can make your readers bored or confused.

Dr. Merlin knows you know this.  She knows you also learn "Show, don't tell."  But she still struggles.  She can find herself in Too Much Information, not the fun kind.

You need to tell the audience what happened.  In film, this is when one character tells another history.  In fiction, you do the telling.

For example, you tell how the heroine met her beloved, got married, and then her husband died.  You don't expect this to take two pages with little dialogue.  You expect to learn about the husband's character.  You expect to see how much he loved his wife.  You expect to see how she changed.

Show the husband's character.  Show his love for his wife.  Show how he changed her.  This will make you care about his death, and about her.

Sometimes, it is good to show not tell.  Show the new character's history without just telling.  Show his Air Force past, his gas station job, his past marriages, his weekend fishing trips, his secret dreams, and his breakfast choice.

Brothers have a special bond. This bond has strong feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and sometimes cruelty. Brothers can understand each other better than anyone else. They see themselves in each other. This bond is especially clear in difficult times. It shows their true character. In times of trouble, this bond shows the good and bad of their feelings.

In "The Scarlet Ibis," two brothers explore this theme. They go on a journey through a beautiful, described landscape. They have strong feelings about each other. In the end, one brother dies. The story shows the feelings of the main character, Doodle, and how he sees the world.

The main character feels pride and anger towards Doodle. He wants Doodle to be like him. He wants to teach him things. But Doodle is weak and cannot do these things. The main character feels angry and sometimes even wants to hurt Doodle. But when Doodle smiles at him, the main character feels love. This shows that his anger is not strong.

The brain is a complex system for processing information. As technology changed from simple to modern, the ways people describe the brain changed too. At first, people said the brain was like a wax tablet, then a sheet of paper, then a book, and now, a computer. As you learn about the brain, remember that these metaphors are useful but can lead to mistakes.

Information starts with signals from the senses. These signals turn physical things like touch, heat, sound, and light into electrical signals. The brain turns these signals into information using two ways: bottom-up and top-down. For example, when you see a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing uses simple information like color and shape to decide it's a box. Top-down processing helps you see it as a box, not a hole in white.

The brain has a filter to decide if information is important. For example, when you look down, you don't see every blade of grass, but you can hear your name in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the filter helps decide which parts are important.

The brain stores information. There are many types of memory, like short-term and long-term. Short-term memory stores information for a few seconds, and long-term memory stores it for a long time.

Many models describe how knowledge is organized in the brain. Some use how people remember things, others use computer science, and some use how neurons work. One model says that there are nodes for concepts, and nodes are linked if they are similar. For example, “chair” can be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden.”

Aldous Huxley criticizes the danger of technology and capitalism in his novel Brave New World. The society values community over individuals. People are made to want happiness. They are like chess pieces, controlled by the World Controller. Looking at the book through Marxist eyes, we see Huxley's warnings about this system.

Marxism uses words like homogeny and reification. This shows Huxley's criticism of the economy. Capitalism is mocked through false consciousness. People do not know about class relations. They only care about their own gain. The World Controller controls this. The common people have no will. They are made to love spending. The lower classes are not aware of this.

In Brave New World, there are no deep relationships. People talk only about physical attractiveness. They obey their place in society. This shows the effect of capitalism. They are like Marx's idea of the proletariat, happy as long as they keep consuming.

I have been student here at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Getting around campus can be hard. My first year, I lived in East Halls. It was very far from classes like in Willard building. It took 25 minutes to walk, and the weather was often bad. Now, there are sports fields and new buildings in that area. Campus is getting bigger, so moving around is tougher. What is the best solution? Bicycles are good, but students need to use them, and the campus needs to be safe for bike riders.

I talked to a friend who rode a bike again after not using one for years. He said, "Bikes are great. It’s the best way to get around." Biking is healthy and fast. A bowl of oatmeal and some exercise can take you 30 miles. I live off campus, far from the center. Buying a bike was the best decision. I now have class in Thomas building. It’s 25 minutes by walk. Biking takes 5 minutes. The only problem is Pollock Road. It's not easy to ride on. I'm too busy to walk, so I need my bike. Walking to Thomas every day would take 30-40 minutes, more than two and a half hours a week. That’s a lot of time I can't afford to waste.
